=== TASK ===
# Study Library (Content List)

## Overview
Build the Study Library (Content List) page for StudySpark, a parent-facing library that presents all saved studies, folders, tags, and filters with bulk actions (export, share, move, delete). The page should support a folder tree with drag-and-drop study assignment, a responsive study grid/list with rich metadata, full-text search, multi-criteria filters, bulk actions, and scalable navigation (pagination or infinite scroll). All code must be runtime-safe against null/undefined values and follow the project’s strict coding standards for arrays and API responses.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
The Study Library (Content List) page is the primary content-management hub for parents. It consolidates saved studies, folders, and tags into an organized, searchable, and filterable library. Goals:

- Provide a clear, welcoming interface to browse, locate, and manage studies.
- Enable folder-based organization with create/rename/delete folders and drag-and-drop of studies into folders.
- Present studies as cards in a responsive grid or list, each showing thumbnail, title, child tags (e.g., subject, learning style), last modified date, and quick actions (Open, Duplicate, Export, Share, Delete).
- Support robust search and filters: full-text search, filters by child, learning style, subject, date range, and starred items.
- Allow bulk actions via a Bulk Actions Bar: select multiple studies and perform Export, Delete, Move, or Share.
- Provide pagination or infinite scrolling for large libraries, with smooth loading indicators.
- Integrate with the app’s design system and ensure accessible contrast, responsive behavior, and delightful micro-interactions.

UI elements and behavior specifics:

- Folder Tree
  - Left-side collapsible tree with folders and subfolders.
  - Actions: Create Folder, Rename Folder, Delete Folder.
  - Drag-and-drop: Allow dragging studies from the grid into folders; show drag-over states.
  - Visual indicators for nesting, counts, and active folder highlight.

- Study Grid / List
  - Cards with thumbnail, title, badges for subject/learning style, last modified, and a compact action bar.
  - Quick actions: Open, Duplicate, Export, Share, Delete (with confirmation for destructive actions).
  - Visual emphasis on the active/selected study, with hover states giving subtle elevation.
  - Support for list view toggle for accessibility or user preference.

- Search & Filters
  - Full-text search input with clear button and keyboard accessibility.
  - Filter panel or top bar with:
    - Child(s)
    - Subject
    - Learning Style
    - Date Range (From/To)
    - Starred items toggle
  - Clear all filters button
  - Real-time results as filters change (debounced input where appropriate)

- Bulk Actions Bar
  - Appears when at least one study is selected.
  - Bulk actions: Export, Share, Move (to folder), Delete
  - Offers "Select All" in current view and per-page selection.
  - Visual cue of how many items are selected.

- Pagination / Infinite Scroll
  - If large libraries: provide pagination controls (page numbers, next/previous) and/or infinite scrolling with a loading indicator and a guard against excessive simultaneous loads.
  - Ensure re-fetch consistency when filters or folder context change.

- Visual Style and Behavior
  - Follow the provided visual style: soft pastel peach, muted lavender, bright tangerine, with gradients, rounded cards, and friendly typography.
  - Cards: 20–28px corner radii, subtle shadows, light borders or none, hover state with elevation.
  - Navigation: Top bar with user avatar, progress or status; bottom navigation as described in the project guidelines.
  - Data visualization: optional usage for stats; if displayed, use pastel fills and rounded bars.
  - Interactive elements: micro-interactions on hover/click, smooth transitions, accessible focus states.

## Components to Build
- StudyLibraryPage
  - Container for overall layout; orchestrates data fetching, state, and interactions.
- FolderTree
  - Tree component with drag-and-drop support; create/rename/delete; drag studies into folders.
- StudyCard
  - Reusable card for a single study; displays thumbnail, title, tags, last modified, and quick actions.
- BulkActionsBar
  - Appears when selected items exist; handles bulk Export, Share, Move, Delete.
- SearchBar
  - Debounced text input with clear action and accessibility features.
- FilterPanel
  - UI for selecting Child, Subject, Learning Style, Date Range, Starred; integrated with URL/state.
- StudyGrid / StudyListView
  - Grid or List rendering of StudyCard components; supports view toggle and responsive breakpoints.
- Pagination / InfiniteScroll
  - Handles loading more items when needed; user feedback for loading states and end-of-list.
- APIAbstractLayer (Data layer)
  - Centralized data fetching hooks for studies, folders, and tags with safe defaults; enforces data ?? [] at every step.
- DragAndDropProvider
  - Handles drag-and-drop events for moving studies to folders with proper accessibility.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React with TypeScript (or the project’s chosen stack).
- State management: useState/useEffect for local state; useReducer or context for shared state if needed.
- Data safety:
  - Always guard array operations: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize arrays with correct defaults: useState<StudyCardType[]>([]) and useState<FolderType[]>([]).
  - Supabase-style results: const studies = data ?? [].
  - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Data models:
  - Study: id, title, thumbnailUrl, lastModified, subject, learningStyle, childId(s), folderId, tags[], isStarred, etc.
  - Folder: id, name, parentFolderId, childCount, color or icon, position/order.
  - Tag: id, name, category.
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive controls have ARIA labels; keyboard navigation supported.
  - High-contrast text on colored backgrounds; sufficient contrast for all UI elements.
- Performance:
  - Debounce search input; throttle or batch filter updates; lazy-load or pagination for large datasets.
- Drag-and-Drop:
  - Implement HTML5 drag-and-drop or library‑based solution with accessible fallbacks.
  - Update folder assignment on drop; optimistic UI with rollback on error.
- Error handling:
  - Graceful fallbacks if folders or studies fail to load; show empty-state messaging with actions.
- Testing considerations:
  - Unit tests for pure helpers (data shaping, defaults).
  - Integration tests for bulk actions and drag-and-drop logic.
  - E2E tests for search, filter, and bulk export/share flows.

### Backend
- APIs (assumed REST or GraphQL as per project norms):
  - GET /studies with query params for search, filters, pagination, and folder context.
  - GET /folders for tree; POST /folders to create; PUT /folders/{id} for rename; DELETE /folders/{id} to remove; POST /folders/{id}/move to relocate studies.
  - POST /studies/{id}/duplicate
  - POST /studies/export (bulk) or individual export endpoint per study
  - POST /studies/share (bulk or per-study)
- Database schema (summary):
  - studies(id PK, title, thumbnailUrl, lastModified, subjectId, learningStyleId, childId, folderId, isStarred boolean, tags JSONB, metadata JSONB, etc.)
  - folders(id PK, name, parentFolderId, position, color)
  - tags(id PK, name, category)
  - study_tags(studyId, tagId)
  - users(id PK, role, permissions)
- Data safety:
  - Ensure API responses are validated; provide empty arrays when no data.
  - Ensure null-safe shapes: response?.data ?? [].
- Bulk operations:
  - Support batch export/share/move/delete with proper transaction boundaries and rollback on failure.
- Security:
  - Authenticated endpoints; authorize access to user’s studies/folders.
- Validation:
  - Validate inputs for folder operations, moves, and bulk actions; sanitize strings.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - StudyLibraryPage fetches folders and studies via API layer; FolderTree updates cause refetch or optimistic updates; StudyGrid re-renders on state changes.
  - SearchBar and FilterPanel produce query parameters that refresh data via the API layer.
  - BulkActionsBar dispatches actions that mutate studies/folders and update UI accordingly.
  - Drag-and-drop triggers move operations through the Folder API; optimistic UI update followed by confirmation.
- State synchronization:
  - Use URL query params to reflect current search/filters/folder for shareable/bookmarkable state.
  - Persist user preferences (view mode: grid/list, sort order, items per page) in localStorage or user profile.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on Study Library (Content List) page.
2. Left-side folder tree loads; user can create/rename/delete folders.
3. User enters a search term in the Search Bar; results refresh in real-time (debounced).
4. User applies filters (child, subject, learning style, date range, starred).
5. Library displays studies as cards in the grid; each card shows thumbnail, title, tags, last modified, and actions.
6. User selects one or more studies via checkboxes or card selection.
7. Bulk Actions Bar appears with options: Export, Share, Move, Delete; user can move to a folder via a dropdown.
8. User drags a study onto a folder in the Folder Tree to re-home it; UI shows drag-over state and confirms on drop.
9. User opens a study to review; can Duplicate, Export, Share, or Delete individually from the card menu.
10. If many studies exist, user can navigate via pagination or enable infinite scrolling to load more.
11. All actions reflect in real-time UI with subtle transitions; empty states guide users to create folders or add studies.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models:
- StudyCardType:
  - id: string
  - title: string
  - thumbnailUrl?: string
  - lastModified: string (ISO date)
  - subjectId?: string
  - learningStyleId?: string
  - childId?: string
  - folderId?: string
  - tags?: string[]
  - isStarred?: boolean
- FolderType:
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - parentFolderId?: string | null
  - position?: number
  - color?: string
- TagType:
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - category?: string
API Endpoints (examples; adapt to project routing conventions):
- GET /api/studies?search=&childId=&subjectId=&learningStyleId=&startDate=&endDate=&starred=&folderId=&page=&pageSize=
- GET /api/folders
- POST /api/folders (name, parentFolderId)
- PUT /api/folders/{id} (name)
- DELETE /api/folders/{id}
- POST /api/folders/{folderId}/move (studyIds[], targetFolderId)
- POST /api/studies/{id}/duplicate
- POST /api/studies/export (studyIds[])
- POST /api/studies/share (studyIds[], shareToUser or public)
Security:
- Use authenticated requests; user must own studies/folders being accessed.
- Validate scopes/permissions before destructive actions.
Validation:
- Validate inputs for IDs (string), IDs exist in current state when performing moves.
- Date range checks (startDate <= endDate); ensure filters produce valid results.

